\description{
Fits a Kernel Regularized Least Squares model with Gaussian kernel,
selecting the ridge penalty by leave-one-out cross-validation via the
closed-form identity of Hainmueller and Hazlett (2014).  Marginal
effects and their variances are computed by default and returned on
the original \verb{(X, y)} scale.
}
\details{
Three call styles are supported (mirrors \code{ares()}):
\itemize{
\item \code{krls(X, y, ...)}  -- matrix / numeric interface (back-compatible).
\item \code{krls(y ~ x1 + x2 + ..., data = df, ...)} -- formula interface
with factor expansion and derived terms (\code{I(x^2)}, \code{poly(x, 2)},
etc).
\item \code{krls(df, y, ...)} where \code{df} is a data frame with numeric +
factor / character columns -- expands categorical columns via
\code{model.matrix(~ ., df)} (treatment contrasts, intercept dropped).
}

The numerical pipeline mirrors \code{KRLS::krls()} exactly:
\enumerate{
\item \code{X} and \code{y} are standardised (column-centred, unit sd).
\item The Gaussian kernel \verb{K_ij = exp(-||x_i - x_j||^2 / sigma)} is built
in parallel C++.
\item \code{K} is eigendecomposed.  All subsequent solves use the
eigen-basis closed forms, never inverting \verb{K + lambda I} directly.
\item \code{lambda} is selected by golden-section search on the closed-form
LOO error sum, with the same \verb{(L, U, tol)} bracket as \code{KRLS::krls}.
\item Marginal effects use the closed-form identity
\verb{dy/dx_k = -(2/sigma) * (X_k * (K c) - K diag(c) X)_k}, computed
without forming the \verb{n x n} distance matrix.
\item Output is unstandardised back to the original \verb{(X, y)} scale.
}

At a fixed \verb{(sigma, lambda)}, fits agree with \code{KRLS::krls()} to
floating-point precision (typically \verb{< 1e-12} on coefficients,
fitted values, and marginal effects for \code{n <= 1000}).  Wall-clock
time is roughly \verb{6-10x} faster than \code{KRLS::krls()} at \code{n >= 500}
when marginal effects and variance estimates are requested.

Memory scales as \code{O(n^2)}: the kernel and its squared eigenvector
matrix are both stored.  Expect about \code{0.4 * n^2 / 1e6} MB of
peak working memory (e.g. ~400MB at \code{n = 1000}, ~10GB at \code{n = 5000}).

\strong{Scale-aware sigma default (geomean_p anchor, v0.0.0.9041)}

When \code{sigma = NULL}, roadrunner sets the Gaussian-kernel bandwidth using the
\emph{geomean_p} formula: let \verb{d2_ij = ||Xs_i - Xs_j||^2} be the pairwise squared
Euclidean distances on the standardised predictor matrix \code{Xs}; then
\code{sigma = sqrt(median({d2_ij : i < j}) * ncol(Xs))}.  This is the geometric
mean of the raw median heuristic and \code{p = ncol(X)}, and empirically lands in
the sweet spot between the two extremes.  At \verb{n=500, p=10} on standardised
N(0,1) data it yields \code{sigma ~ 13.5}, versus \code{~ 18-19} for the raw median
and \code{10} for \code{KRLS::krls()}'s fixed default.

\strong{Why geomean_p}: a 15-DGP head-to-head vs \code{KRLS::krls()} (REQ-20260518-003,
iter-2) with the geomean_p anchor shows roadrunner \strong{wins 12/15 DGPs, loses
0/15, ties 3/15}.  The raw median anchor (v0.0.0.9040) won only 4/15 DGPs
because it over-smoothed locally nonlinear signals (exp-decay, interaction,
tanh-interaction, poly2) by selecting sigma ~2x too wide.  The geomean_p
anchor preserves scale-awareness (adapts to the actual data distribution,
unlike the hard-coded \code{sigma = p}) while avoiding over-smoothing.

For \code{n > 500} the pairwise distance matrix is \code{O(n^2)}; to keep the default
cheap, a 500-row subsample is drawn with a fixed seed (\code{set.seed(2718)}) so
the result is deterministic within a session.

\strong{Autotune-equals-default equivalence at well-fit settings}

When autotune is enabled at settings where the default sigma is already near-
optimal (e.g. additive and interaction DGPs at \verb{n=500, p=10}), the autotune
grid is centred on \code{sigma_anchor} and the CV argmin coincides with the grid
centre.  The 1-SE rule then selects \code{sigma_anchor}, producing a fit identical
to the non-autotuned default.  This is the expected behaviour — it confirms
that the default sigma is well-chosen for these DGPs — not a failure of
autotune.  Autotune yields improvements when the optimal sigma departs from
the anchor (e.g. sparse / linear DGPs where a much wider kernel is better).

Since v0.0.0.9042 the autotune inner loop is parallelised over sigma
candidates using \code{RcppParallel} (TBB). The pairwise squared-distance
matrix is computed once per CV fold and reused across every sigma in
the grid (\code{exp(-D / sigma)} is then a cheap elementwise op).
Determinism is preserved: each worker writes to a unique slot in the
output vectors, so the result is byte-identical regardless of
\code{autotune.nthreads}. Pass \code{autotune.nthreads = 1} to force strictly
sequential execution.
}
\note{
At a fixed \verb{(sigma, lambda)} fits remain byte-identical to all earlier
versions of roadrunner KRLS.  The four defaults changed in v0.0.0.9040
(\code{sigma}, \code{tol}, autotune nfold/ncross, autotune grid) only affect results
when those arguments are left at \code{NULL} / at their default.  Restore any
old default explicitly: \code{sigma = ncol(X)}, \code{tol = 1e-3 * nrow(X)},
\code{nfold = 5}, \code{ncross = 1}, \code{autotune.grid = ncol(X) * c(0.25, 0.5, 1, 2, 4, 8)}.

The sigma anchor formula was refined in v0.0.0.9041 from the raw median
(\code{median(d2)}) to the geomean_p formula (\code{sqrt(median(d2) * p)}).  To
restore the v0.0.0.9040 median anchor, pass
\code{sigma = stats::median(as.numeric(stats::dist(scale(X)))^2)}.

Phase 1 speedup (v0.0.0.9042): parallel autotune assumes single-threaded
BLAS for the small kernel operations inside the parallel region. If you
have set a high process-global BLAS thread count (e.g. via
\code{RhpcBLASctl::blas_set_num_threads(8)}), consider resetting to 1 around
\code{krls(..., autotune = TRUE)} calls to avoid oversubscription. The
BLAS-heavy distance computation runs OUTSIDE the parallel region and
benefits from multi-threaded BLAS.
}
\examples{
set.seed(1)
n <- 100
X <- matrix(rnorm(n * 3), n, 3)
colnames(X) <- c("age", "income", "score")
y <- sin(X[, 1]) + 0.5 * X[, 2]^2 - 0.3 * X[, 3] +
  rnorm(n, sd = 0.2)

fit <- krls(X, y)
fit
fit$avgderivatives           # average marginal effect per variable
summary(fit)

## Formula interface with mixed numeric + factor predictors.
df <- data.frame(age = X[, 1], income = X[, 2],
                 region = factor(sample(c("N", "S"), n, replace = TRUE)),
                 y = y)
fit_f <- krls(y ~ age + income + region, data = df)

## Predictions on new data with pointwise SEs.
Xnew <- matrix(rnorm(20 * 3), 20, 3)
colnames(Xnew) <- colnames(X)
pr <- predict(fit, Xnew, se.fit = TRUE)
head(pr$fit)
head(pr$se.fit)

}
\references{
Hainmueller, J. and C. Hazlett (2014).  "Kernel
Regularized Least Squares: Reducing Misspecification Bias with a
Flexible and Interpretable Machine Learning Approach."  \emph{Political
Analysis} 22(2):143--168.
}
